Objectives / Learning Outcome(s) / Major:
TOPIC OUTLINE:
THE ROLE OF ACCOUNTING IN BUSINESS;
BASIC ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS;
ACCRUAL ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS; 
SARBANES-OXLEY AND INTERNAL CONTROLS;
ACCOUNTING FOR MERCHANDISING BUSINESSES; 
ACCOUNTING FOR MANUFACTURING BUSINESSES;
ASSETS, LIABILITIES, AND OWNER EQUITY;
FINANCIAL STATEMENT ANALYSIS;
COST BEHAVIOR AND COST-VOLUME-PROFIT ANALYSIS;
DIFFERENTIAL ANALYSIS AND PRODUCT PRICING;
BUDGETING AND STANDARD COST SYSTEMS;
CAPITAL INVESTMENT ANALYSIS.

LEARNING OUTCOMES:

1. PREPARE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS FOR BOTH PROFIT AND NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS BY USING ACCOUNTING TERMINOLOGY AND CONCEPTS.
2. EVALUATE ETHICAL PRACTICES AND USE THEM IN ESTABLISHING A VIABLE FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT STRATEGY.
3. ANALYZE AND INTERPRET FINANCIAL STATEMENTS FOR BOTH PROFIT AND NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS.
4. CALCULATE FINANCIAL RATIOS AND APPLY IN THE ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE.
5. APPLY DECISION MAKING TECHNIQUES USING 
COST-VOLUME-PROFIT AND DIFFERENTIAL ANALYSIS.
6. PREPARE AND EXPLAIN AN OPERATING BUDGET AND A CAPITAL EXPENSE BUDGET.
7. EMPLOY THE RELATIONSHIPS EXISTING BETWEEN PLANNING, DIRECTING, BUDGETING IN ESTABLISHING FINANCIAL CONTROLS.
8. USE THE TOOLS OF MANAGERIAL ACCOUNTING TO COMMUNICATE BUSINESS DECISIONS BY ANALYZING CASE STUDIES.
9. APPLY ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES AND PROCEDURES WITHIN THE CONTEXT OF THE STUDENTS MAJOR DISCIPLINE CONCENTRATION.
